355–Female":"1355–Afdød","about 1392":"omkring 1392","1422":"1422","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1376":"1376","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1376–1395":"1376–1395","1372–1392":"1372–1392","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1300–Male":"1300–Overleden","1355–Female":"1355–Overleden","about 1392":"circa 1392","1422":"1422","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1376":"1376","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1376–1395":"1376–1395","1372–1392":"1372–1392","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1355–Female":"1355–Deceased","about 1392":"about 1392","1422":"1422","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1376":"1376","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Corbett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (West Midlands, of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>corbet</i> ‘raven’, probably denoting someone with dark hair or a dark complexion.","History: This is the name of a family descended from Hugh <i>Corbet</i>, a Norman baron who settled in Shropshire following the Norman Conquest. One of his descendants, Sir Richard Corbet, was granted land near Shrewsbury in 1223; since the 13th century, this place has been known as Moreton Corbet. The name was taken from Shropshire to Scotland in the 12th century and to northern Ireland in the 17th century, and thence to North America by at least one group of bearers of the name."],"variants":[{"name":"Corbit","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Corbett  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Corb","meanings":["English (Durham): nickname from Middle English <i>corb</i> ‘raven’ (from Old French <i>corb</i>; compare   Corbett  ,   Corbin  )."]},{"name":"Corbet","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Corbett  .","History: Walter Corbet, a royal knight in 12th-century Scotland, was the first of that name in that kingdom. His 13th-century descendants were major landholders in the Borders, and in the 14th century they acquired lands in the North of Scotland."]},{"name":"Corbitt","meanings":["English: variant of   Corbett  .","Irish: variant of   Corban  ."]},{"name":"Corban","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Corbáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Corbán</i>’ or <b>Ó Coirbín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Coirbín</i>’, both possibly from an occupational name based on <i>corb</i> ‘chariot’. Both names have also been Anglicized as   Corbett  .","Irish: alternatively, a variant of <b>Currivan</b>, from <b>Ó Coirbheáin</b>, itself a variant of   Corban   (pronounced with three syllables in Irish).","Romanian: nickname derived from <i>corb</i> ‘crow’, with the augmentative suffix <i>-an</i>."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Corbett was born in 1376, in Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Walter Corbett, was 76 and her mother, Emma Oddingseles, was 22. She married William Dennis Esq. about 1392, in Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1395, in her hometown, at the age of 19."},"et":{"1376–1395":"1376–1395","1372–1392":"1372–1392","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1355–Female":"1355–Surnud","about 1392":"umbes 1392","1422":"1422","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1376":"1376","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1376–1395":"1376–1395","1372–1392":"1372–1392","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1355–Female":"1355–Kuollut","about 1392":"noin 1392","1422":"1422","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1376":"1376","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1376–1395":"1376–1395","1372–1392":"1372–1392","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","1355–Female":"1355–Décédée","about 1392":"environ 1392","1422":"1422","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1376":"1376","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Margaret Corbett est née en 1376, à Alveston, Gloucestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Walter Corbett, avait 76 ans et sa mère, Emma Oddingseles, avait 22 ans. Elle a épousé William Dennis Esq. environ 1392, à Alveston, Gloucestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Elle est décédée en 1395, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 19 ans."},"de":{"1376–1395":"1376–1395","1372–1392":"1372–1392","1360–1422":"1360–1422","1300–Male":"1300–Verstorben","1355–Female":"1355–Verstorben